@node not07 "AMIGA MEETING IN READING, ENGLAND"
                       AMIGA MEETING IN READING, ENGLAND
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Held on January 20, 2000

A Report by Open Amiga - January 23, 2000
By Open Amiga President, Steve Crietzman

   - Background

In a phonecall with Bill McEwen, President & CEO of Amiga, COSA was informed
that a gathering of prominent members of the Amiga community was taking place in
Reading, England. We were invited to attend, and told that we should contact
Andrew Korn, Editor of AmigaActive, for more information.

We happily obliged, and on the 20th January 2000, I was present in a room with
room - a Tandori restaurant to be exact - with approximately 25 other Amigans -
everyone from Bill McEwen and Fleecy of Amino, Tao Chairman Francis Charig, Mick
Tinker of BoXeR fame, Andrew Korn and David Stroud from AmigaActive, Ben Vost
(Amiga Format), Olaf Barthel (OS 3.5), and many others whose names escape me
right now.

The story, of course, doesn't begin there.

It begins at a pub called the Hope Tap. I arrived early, 5:15pm to be precise,
while the meeting was schedule to begin at 6pm. I was in town at the time, and
decided I'd get a few early drinks while I await the rest of the gang to appear.

Six o' clock comes and I'm starting to get worried. Until I realise they had
quietly been gathering in a place where I couldn't easily see them from my
position up front at the bar. So I go over, and sit down next to Ben Vost.

Well, Bill and Fleecy still hadn't turned up by this point, so I was beginning
to get a little concerned. We all assumed they were going to be a little late,
so we were patient. We waited. And waited. And waited. 6pm came and went. So did
7pm. So did 8pm.

By now, I was getting very worried. I had come down mainly to discuss a few open
source issues with Fleecy and Bill relating to patents, trademarks and various
source code issues that had been raised and which AROS members had passed onto
COSA to ask at the meeting. I had even booked a night at a reasonably expensive
hotel, and was beginning to feel it had been a waste of money.

So, at 8:30pm, myself, Ben Vost, and about half a dozen of us decided we weren't
going to wait any longer. So the AF group headed off to the Tandori we had
arranged to meet at. The AmigaActive Crew stayed behind.

So, around 9pm we arrived at the Tandori restaurant. No tables had been reserved
by Mr. McEwen. Or Mr. Moss. We started to worry. Then the guy we were talking to
suddenly said, "We have a booking for Amiga?" A huge sigh of relief all around.
"They are over there at the back. They've been waiting for you since 6:30pm."

   - The Evening Begins - At Last

So, after the mess had been cleared up, and the confusion cleared, we all began
to sat down. Of course, I did point out that really someone ought to go back and
tell the AmigaActive gang. Of course, people just grinned and we decided to be
seated. They'd figure it out eventually ;)

And we were right. At 9:30pm, they all arrived. Now the meeting could begin. It
may be over 3hrs late, but who's counting. Shit happens.

And so we all began to sit down. Not long after we were all together, Bill
McEwen introduced everyone and started to pass around Non Disclosure Agreements.
This meant that anything we would hear from Bill or Fleecy on "The Presentation"
would have to remain a secret. The subject, of course, was the future of Amiga.
That much I'm sure you could have all guessed. What you couldn't have guessed
followed in Bill and Fleecy's almost two-to-three-hour presentation speech that
followed.

As well as being treated to a wonderfully energetic and information-packed
session, we were treated to lots of Indian food, curries and beers etc, all paid
for on Amiga's tab. Whoever said there's no such thing as a free lunch? I had
lunch, and it was free. At least, it was free for me. That's all that mattered -
I had lunch, and it was free to me. ;)

The AmigaActive crew was giving away free issues of their magazine, including
sneak previews of their next issue. Most everyone else, including Bill McEwen,
Francis Charig etc. were giving away business cards. I felt left out. If I would
have known that this was the "in thing" to do, I would have created a few COSA
business cards for everyone. Oh well. I'll know next time.

Everything was wonderfully informal, fun and rousing. Enthusiasm was definately
present in that room, although of course a few people privately expressed
concern in private after the presentation, about the lack of any connection with
the Classic Amiga. Everyone was pleased to hear, however, that H&P would be
developing AmigaOS 3.x and 4.x for PPC, having been given permission to do so by
Bill and Fleecy's Amiga.

   - COSA and Open Source

I was obviously there as a representative for COSA, and so I would be remiss if
I didn't cover the open-source issues that were mentioned at the party.

Fleecy Moss publicly confirmed Amino's support for an open source future for
AmigaOS and gave backing to COSA and AROS to "do what [we] could with it."

He did add, however, that there were legal and patent issues involved that were
far more complicated than anyone could have anticipated. COSA was already braced
for the news that patents would have to be addressed, but we suspected it would
be a relatively straightforward matter, of getting the OK from Gateway to use
them, write up an Open Source License granting permission for them to be used in
AmigaOS, end of story.

But it is not quite that simple. The patents have been registered under a
variety of names, of companies and individuals, and many obstacles still exist
that need to be worked through. So it could take time. Amiga are committed to it
happening however, they genuinely support and back the idea, and want to "give
the AmigaOS back to the community that made it what it is." And so they have set
their lawyers on the task, as of three weeks ago. Their task is to make
open-source legally "okay", then make it happen.

We also discussed with Mick Tinker our plans to produce and sell Kickstart ROMs
burned with Kickstart ROMs created by COSA/AROS, and the shortage of
AMD27C200/MX27C2100 and AMD27C400/MX27C4100 EPROMs, the type used on the Amiga
motherboard for the Kickstart ROMs. He responded by informing us that the BoXeR
uses Flash ROMs, bypassing this problem, to which we are relieved to hear.
Upgrading older Classic Amigas, however, may pose more of a problem - but not a
problem that cannot be deconstructed.

We briefly discussed with Olaf Barthel the subject of OS 3.5 and open source. He
confirmed he is not opposed to open source, but does feel that such an endeavour
needs to be carefully and diligently handled, a fact on which both COSA/AROS and
Olaf Barthel are in total agreement. A fact which refutes claims in the press
that we are "at odds", or that we have opposing views on the subject. We do have
differences of opinion, to be sure, but we are not trying to destroy each other
as in a matter/antimatter reaction - just discuss some concerns. It was a
pleasure to meet Mr. Barthel, and I repeat here what I told him there: OS 3.5 is
a wonderful piece of work, and we owe him. Thanks, Olaf, for helping to create a
great product!

   - Summary and Conclusion

I found the meeting fun, enjoyable, exciting and uplifting. It was nice to be
able to meet up with fellow Amigans and to get to put faces to names. Ben Vost
tried to lure me into a debate on Open Source, but I passed on the opportunity
and worked to end the debate as quickly as possible. I wasn't there to debate or
argue, and wasn't about to be lured into that old trap. If Ben wants to hear
COSA's arguments in favour of open source, and to write a piece for AF, he's
going to have to try a different way :)

AmigaActive, to their credit, did not take such a confrontational attitude,
instead offering us the chance to write an article for the next issue of
AmigaActive, an offer I have greatfully accepted :) Look for a 350-700 word
article in a future issue of AA.

To conclude, all I can say is that I am excited by Amino's plans for the future,
and excited by their continuing support for Open Source. If they keep their
promise to Open Source the OS if possible, and it is possible, that will allow
COSA/AROS's collective dreams to become a reality. (To that end, COSA is
preparing a formal Strategy Brief which we hope to have ready soon.)

The hard work now begins, and COSA must make some structural and organisational
changes in order to be ready for the day that AmigaOS goes Open Source. We need
to become a nonprofit corporation and appoint our first board of directors. We
need to become a registered nonprofit foundation and create our articles of
incorporation, a formal mission statement, open a corporate bank account, and
such like. I am personally looking forward to the challenge, which I will
embrace. The future with Amino looks bright for both the Classic OS and systems
(through COSA/AROS), and the next generation OS and systems (through
Amiga/Amino).

Let's get going. Whether your heart lies with the Classic and COSA/AROS, or with
the next-generation systems of Amiga/Amino, we finally are "Back for the Future"
!

Steve Crietzman
President, Open Amiga Group
(formerly known as COSA)
